#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/gemstones/sed_search_replace.md:15
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using `sed`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/gemstones/sed_search_replace.md:18
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using `sed` for search and replace is my personal preference because you can use a delimiter of your choice, which makes replacing things like web links with “/” in them very handy. The default examples for in place editing using `sed` show things like this example:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/gemstones/sed_search_replace.md:20
#, no-wrap
msgid "`sed -i 's/search_for/replace_with/g' /path/filename`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/gemstones/sed_search_replace.md:22
#, no-wrap
msgid "But what if you are searching for strings that will contain \"/\" in them? If the forward slash was the only option available as a delimiter, then we would have to escape each forward slash before we could use it in the search. That's where `sed` excels over other tools, because the delimiter is changeable on-the-fly (no need to specify that you are changing it anywhere). As stated, if we are looking for things with \"/\" in them, we can easily do that by changing the delimiter to \"|\". Here's an example of looking for a link using this method:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/gemstones/sed_search_replace.md:24
#, no-wrap
msgid "`sed -i 's|search_for/with_slash|replace_string|g' /path/filename`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/gemstones/sed_search_replace.md:26
#, no-wrap
msgid "You can use any single-byte character for the delimiter with the exception of backslash, newline, and \"s\". For instance, this works too:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/gemstones/sed_search_replace.md:28
#, no-wrap
msgid "`sed -i 'sasearch_forawith_slashareplace_stringag' /path/filename` where \"a\" is the delimiter, and the search and replace still works. For safety, you can specify a backup while searching and replacing, which is handy for making sure the changes you are making with `sed` are what you _really_ want. This gives you a recovery option from the backup file:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/gemstones/sed_search_replace.md:30
#, no-wrap
msgid "`sed -i.bak s|search_for|replacea_with|g /path/filename`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/gemstones/sed_search_replace.md:32
#, no-wrap
msgid "Which will create an unedited version of `filename` called `filename.bak`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/gemstones/sed_search_replace.md:34
#, no-wrap
msgid "You can also use full quotes instead of single quotes if you like:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/gemstones/sed_search_replace.md:36
#, no-wrap
msgid "`sed -i \"s|search_for/with_slash|replace_string|g\" /path/filename`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/gemstones/sed_search_replace.md:45
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"|Option | Explanation                                                   |\n"
"|-------|---------------------------------------------------------------|\n"
"| i     | edit file in place                                            |\n"
"| i.ext | create a backup with whatever the extension is (ext here)     |\n"
"| s     | specifies search                                              |\n"
"| g     | specifies to replace globally, in other words all occurrences |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/gemstones/sed_search_replace.md:46
#, no-wrap
msgid "Multiple files"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/gemstones/sed_search_replace.md:49
#, no-wrap
msgid "Unfortunately, `sed` doesn't have an in-line looping option like `perl`. To loop through multiple files, you would need to combine your `sed` command within a script. Here's an example of doing that.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/gemstones/sed_search_replace.md:51
#, no-wrap
msgid "First, generate a list of files that your script will use, which can be entered at the command line:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/gemstones/sed_search_replace.md:53
#, no-wrap
msgid "`find /var/www/html  -name \"*.php\" > phpfiles.txt`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/gemstones/sed_search_replace.md:55
#, no-wrap
msgid "Next, create a script to use this `phpfiles.txt`:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/gemstones/sed_search_replace.md:56
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"#!/bin/bash\n"
"\n"
"for file in `cat phpfiles.txt`\n"
"do\n"
"        sed -i.bak 's|search_for/with_slash|replace_string|g' $file\n"
"done\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/gemstones/sed_search_replace.md:65
#, no-wrap
msgid "The script loops through all of the files created in `phpfiles.txt`, creates a backup of each file, and executes the search and replace string globally.  Once you have verified that your search and replace has completed successfully and your changes are what you want, you can delete all of the backup files.\n"
msgstr ""

